04640nam a22007095i 9781442684652DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162007onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013939276  a97814426846527 a10.3138/97814426846522doi  a(DE-B1597)464029  a(OCoLC)944177148  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aRC552.A44bR48 2007eb 7aPSY0310002bisacsh04a616.85/2252221 aReuter, Shelley Z., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNarrating Social Order :bAgoraphobia and the Politics of Classification /cShelley Z. Reuter. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: A Sociology of Psychiatry -- t2. Urban Modernity and Social Change: Diagnosing Alienation -- t3. Explaining Agoraphobia: Three Frameworks -- t4. The Prerogative of Being ‘Normal’: Gender, ‘Race,’ and Class -- t5. The DSM and the Decline of the Social -- t6. Conclusion: Doing Agoraphobia(s) – The Social Relations of Psychiatric Knowledge -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAgoraphobia, the fear of open spaces, has received minimal attention from sociologists. Yet implicit within psychiatric discussion of this disease is a normative account of society, social order, social ordering, and power relations, making agoraphobia an excellent candidate for sociological interpretation. Narrating Social Order provides the first critical sociological framework for understanding agoraphobia, as well as the issue of psychiatric classification more generally.Shelley Z. Reuter explores three major themes in her analysis: agoraphobia in the context of gender, race, and class; the shift in recent decades from an emphasis on psychoanalytic explanations for mental diseases to an emphasis on strictly biogenic explanations; and, finally, embodiment as a process that occurs in and through disease categories. Reuter provides a close reading of reports of agoraphobia beginning with the first official cases, along with the DSM and its precursors, illustrating how a ?psychiatric narrative? is contained within this clinical discourse. She argues that, while the disease embodies very real physiological and emotional experiences of suffering, implicit in this fluid and shifting discourse are socio-cultural assumptions. These assumptions, and especially the question of what it means, both medically and culturally, to be ?normal? and ?pathological,? demonstrate the overlap between the psychiatric narrative of agoraphobia and socio-cultural narratives of exclusion. Ultimately, Reuter seeks to confront the gap that exists between sociological and psychiatric conceptions of mental disease and to understand the relationship between biomedical and cultural knowledges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAgoraphobia. 0aMental illnessvClassification. 0aSocial psychiatry. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Social Psychology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268465240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442684652423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442684652.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK